nd factional agendas in the early sixteenth-century French court. Spring boarding from the burgeoning scholarship of gender, the political, and power in early modern Europe, the book provides a perspective from the French court, from the reigns of Charles VIII to Henri II, a time at which the French court was a glittering centre of culture and which women are understood to have played increasingly important roles. Cross-disciplinary in its perspectives, these essays by historians, art and literary scholars cohesively investigate the dynamic operations of gendered power in political acts, recognised status as queens and regents, ritualised behaviors such as gift-giving, educational coteries, courtly household organisation, and social networking, literary and artistic patronage, female authorship, and epistolary strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPower (Social sciences)zFrancexHistoryy15th century. 0aPower (Social sciences)zFrancexHistoryy16th century. 0aWomenxHistoryyRenaissance, 1450-1600. 0aWomenzFrancexHistoryy15th century. 0aWomenzFrancexHistoryy16th century. 0aWomenzFrancexSocial conditionsy15th century. 0aWomenzFrancexSocial conditionsy16th century. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aPower, Women, Gender, France, Renaissance.1 aAdams, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouchard, Mawy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromilow, Pollie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroomhall, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct